{
  "text": "In considering Adinkras that are not cubes, but rather quotients of cubes, it is useful to first consider a few examples. First, we consider the N = 4 example obtained by quotienting a four-dimensional cube by identifying antipodal points. This Adinkra was first described in Ref. [CITATION_1] , where it was identified as the dimensional reduction of the D = 4 chiral superfield. Here, we present this example in a way that will motivate the general construction to quotient cubes.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18179363"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "18179363": {
      "title": "Adinkras: A graphical technology for supersymmetric representation theory",
      "abstract": "We present a symbolic method for organizing the representation theory of one-dimensional superalgebras. This relies on special objects, which we have called adinkra symbols, which supply tangible geometric forms to the still-emerging mathematical basis underlying supersymmetry."
    }
  }
}